    "sessionDescription": "Effective support for neurodivergent students depends on strong, trusting partnerships between schools and families. Yet these relationships are often strained by stigma, inconsistent communication, and systems that position families as passive recipients rather than active collaborators.\n\nThis session explores practical, justice-centered strategies for building authentic school–home partnerships with families of neurodivergent learners (including autistic, ADHD, dyslexic, and other learning differences). Participants will examine how bias and deficit-based language can unintentionally erode trust and learn concrete approaches to shift toward strengths-based, culturally responsive collaboration.\n\nEducators will leave with immediately usable tools for communication, problem-solving, and shared decision-making that honor family expertise, center student identity, and promote consistency between home and school supports.",
    "extendedDescription": "This session, “Partnering with Families of Neurodivergent Students: Building Trust, Consistency, and Collaboration,” explores how schools can strengthen equitable and inclusive practices by transforming the way they engage with families of neurodivergent learners. Drawing on my experience as an HR professional specializing in inclusive recruitment, alongside my lived experience as a parent of neurodivergent children, I bring a dual perspective on how systems either build trust—or unintentionally erode it. While my work is rooted in workplace inclusion, the same principles of psychological safety, communication equity, and strengths-based collaboration apply directly to education systems.\n\nAt the core of this session is the idea that justice-centered education requires more than instructional strategies; it requires relational systems built on trust, dignity, and shared expertise. Families of neurodivergent students often navigate repeated experiences of misunderstanding, deficit-based labeling, and inconsistent communication across school systems. These experiences can create barriers to collaboration and limit student success. This session reframes family engagement as a core equity practice rather than an ancillary responsibility.\n\nThe session is structured into four key components. First, participants will examine how bias, language, and system design shape family-school relationships, often unintentionally positioning educators as “experts” while minimizing family knowledge. Second, we will explore the lived experience of families navigating neurodiversity across both home and institutional systems, highlighting where communication breakdowns commonly occur and why trust can be difficult to establish.\n\nThird, the session will focus on practical, actionable strategies for building stronger partnerships. Participants will learn strengths-based communication techniques, including how to reframe challenging conversations, reduce stigma in written and verbal communication, and create consistency between home and school supports. We will also explore structured collaboration tools, such as shared problem-solving frameworks and predictable communication routines that support transparency and follow-through.\n\nFinally, participants will engage in application-based reflection to identify one or two immediate changes they can implement in their own context. These takeaways are designed to be realistic and sustainable, supporting educators in making meaningful shifts without adding significant burden to their workload.\n\nThis session directly aligns with the theme “Justice-Centered Education for a Changing World” by addressing the systemic and relational conditions that impact student belonging and access. In a rapidly changing educational landscape, equity cannot be achieved through instruction alone; it must also be embedded in how schools communicate, collaborate, and build trust with families. By centering neurodivergent learners and their caregivers as essential partners, this session supports educators in creating environments where all students are seen, understood, and supported.\n\nUltimately, this work helps educators move from compliance-driven family engagement toward authentic partnership rooted in equity, respect, and shared responsibility for student success.",
