    "sessionDescription": "Equity requires more than awareness. It requires action, especially in uncomfortable moments. This session uses the Check Your BS® (Belief System) transformational coaching framework and Energy Leadership™ to examine how comfort, avoidance, and unchallenged beliefs show up in education. Participants will learn how to recognize internal barriers and make more intentional choices that support equitable, inclusive learning environments.",
    "extendedDescription": "Let's be clear. Equity requires more than awareness. \n\nIt requires action, especially in moments that feel uncomfortable, uncertain, or high-stakes. Justice-centered education calls for educators and leaders who are willing to examine how their own belief systems influence the way they think, communicate, and show up for students every day.\n\nIn this session, Coach Shaquan introduces the Check Your BS® (Belief System) transformational coaching framework alongside principles from Energy Leadership™ to explore how habitual thoughts shape behavior in educational spaces. These belief systems are often formed through what we have been taught, experienced, or assumed, and they influence how educators respond to students, engage in conversations around equity, and navigate moments that require clarity, courage, and accountability.\n\nEquity will be defined as the ability to recognize how our beliefs, assumptions, and experiences influence how we treat others, and to make intentional choices that create fair and inclusive opportunities for every student to succeed. Participants will examine how “comfort” can show up as avoidance, silence, over-accommodation, or hesitation to address inequities in real time. The session challenges the belief that awareness alone leads to change by focusing on the internal patterns that create a gap between intention and impact.\n\nThis interactive experience introduces a practical, repeatable process to:\n\n• Recognize whether current thoughts are supporting or limiting equitable practices\n• Identify the source of beliefs and how they influence interactions with students and colleagues\n• Name internal barriers such as fear of judgment, conflict, or getting it wrong\n• Challenge beliefs that may no longer serve their role as educators\n• Choose how to show up in alignment with equity, inclusion, and student success\n\nBy connecting self-awareness to everyday choice-making, this session supports educators in creating learning environments where students feel seen, supported, and valued. Participants will leave with language, tools, and a deeper understanding of how internal belief systems influence external outcomes.\n\nThis experience moves beyond inspiration and into transformation, equipping educators with tools they can immediately apply in their personal and professional relationships, as well as in their classrooms and leadership roles.",
