    "sessionDescription": "Here’s a concise, SLU-ready version that keeps the core message intact:\n\nSchools are navigating growing demands around compliance, student behavior, and equitable outcomes, yet many systems were built for accountability rather than belonging or development. This session introduces a Justice-Centered Systems Framework grounded in education reform, juvenile justice, restorative practices, and organizational leadership. It is a field-tested model that redefines how schools approach discipline, culture, and leadership alignment. Participants will examine why reactive discipline systems fall short and how to build proactive environments where belonging is embedded into the structure. Through real-world examples, attendees will leave with practical strategies and a clear, actionable path forward.",
    "extendedDescription": "Schools across the country are navigating an increasingly complex intersection of compliance demands, student behavioral challenges, instructional expectations, and the urgent call for equitable outcomes. Yet many of the systems guiding school operations were designed primarily for accountability and risk management, not for fostering belonging, development, or long-term student success. This session directly aligns with the theme Justice-Centered Education for a Changing World by challenging participants to rethink how systems either reinforce inequities or intentionally disrupt them.\n\nThis session introduces a Justice-Centered Systems Framework grounded in the intersection of education reform, juvenile justice, restorative practices, and organizational leadership. The approach moves beyond theory and centers on a field-tested model that redefines how schools and districts address discipline, compliance, culture, and leadership alignment. Participants will explore how traditional, reactive discipline pipelines disproportionately impact students and staff, and how to shift toward proactive, system-level strategies that embed equity and belonging into daily practice.\n\nThe session will be structured in three parts. First, participants will engage in a systems reflection exercise to assess current practices and identify gaps in alignment, equity, and student experience. Second, the facilitator will introduce the Justice-Centered Systems Framework, highlighting key components such as restorative practices, leadership clarity, and sustainable culture-building strategies. Finally, participants will work through real-world case examples from charter schools, public districts, alternative education settings, and juvenile justice environments to translate concepts into actionable strategies.\n\nBy the end of the session, participants will leave with practical tools, implementation strategies, and a clear roadmap for creating justice-centered systems that improve student outcomes, strengthen school culture, and support sustainable change in an evolving educational landscape.",
