    "sessionDescription": "As the United States faces a mental health crisis, 3.1% of Americans aged 3-17 are affected by anxiety.  Through their vocation, Catholic school teachers are called to serve these students as children of God.  This session reviews concepts of improvement science as they relate to better understanding current systems as well as using data to begin positive change.",
    "extendedDescription": "Introduction\nThis presentation will be created on Mentimeter.  Those in the session will be able to access the presentation through a QR code and participate in various features.\nThis presentation will begin by introducing the state of mental health in the United States.  It will provide statistics on mental health and anxiety in children as well as describe characteristics of generalized anxiety.\nTopic 1: Anxiety in Schools\nThis section will address how anxiety affects students in elementary school.  Hamm’s video Understanding Trauma: Learning Brain vs Survival Brain will be used to describe how anxiety affects students.  Participants will be asked to participate in Mentimeter’s Select Answer feature to respond to the prompt, “Have you had students that seem to have survival brain in the classroom?”\nThe presentation will then address how Catholic school teachers are positioned to serve students with anxiety through a vocation to participate in the Church’s evangelizing mission (Miller, 2006), leading by Christ’s example.\nTopic 2: Social Emotional Learning\nThis section of the presentation will focus on social emotional learning (SEL).  Its definition and how it contributes to mental health in schools will be discussed, citing the Collaborative for Academic, Social, and Emotional Learning and its graphics.\nOpenlight Media’s Catholic SEL framework will be presented, and Villa & Rassmussen’s parallel between the Carthusian motto “The cross of Christ is still in the turning world” and teacher vocation will be discussed.\nResults from Hamilton & Doss’ 2019 teacher survey on SEL will be presented.  Then, participants will answer some of the same survey questions using Mentimeter’s Scales feature.  For example, participants will respond to questions about self-efficacy and responsibility regarding SEL on a scale.\nTopic 3: Improvement Science\nThis section of the presentation will introduce Bryk et, al.’s definitions and concepts of improvement science and how teachers can use them to improve practice when it comes to meeting the needs of students with anxiety in the classroom.\nThe presentation will describe how a casual systems analysis is one method that can be used by teachers through improvement networks to identify what needs to be improved.  Journey lines and focus groups will be defined and examples will be provided.  Participants will have time to brainstorm responses to the question, “Reflect on one or two experiences within the last seven years in which you adjusted your routines and/or instruction to meet the needs of a student with characteristics of generalized anxiety.  Be sure to note any obstacles you encountered during these experiences.”  Then, participants will be able to share answers using Mentimeter’s Open Ended feature, which will then contribute to a focus group discussion.\nSaldaña’s qualitative coding and fishbone diagrams will be discussed.  Together, the group will create a fishbone diagram and discuss next steps: networked improvement communities, an improvement map, and a driver diagram.\nConclusion\nThe presentation will end with an overview of topics addressed as well as a question and answer session.  Mentimenter’s Q&A feature will be used to present the questions to everyone for facilitated discussion.",
