    "id": "speaker-7",
    "name": "Dr. Jami Edwards",
    "role": "Elementary Teacher",
    "organization": "Mascoutah School District",
    "bio": "Jami Edwards, Ed.D., is a fifth-grade teacher and educational leader in Mascoutah, Illinois, with over a decade of experience in diverse school settings, including Saint Louis Public Schools. Her doctoral research at Saint Louis University focused on Collective Teacher Efficacy and its impact on equity, leadership, and student outcomes. Jami is passionate about building collaborative school cultures grounded in trust, high expectations, and shared responsibility for all students. She is committed to bridging research and practice to create meaningful, lasting change in schools.",
    "presentationExperience": "Jami Edwards, Ed.D., has experience presenting to educators in both urban and suburban settings. She has led professional learning sessions for staff in Saint Louis Public Schools focused on effectively using ClassDojo to strengthen communication and student engagement. In Mascoutah, she has presented to new teachers across the district, supporting their transition into the district and sharing practical strategies for classroom success. Her presentations are grounded in real-world experience and designed to provide clear, actionable takeaways for educators.",
    "image": "https://drive.google.com/u/2/open?usp=forms_web&id=1txUYaZ0bLoGcDh_gxrZsprDAUujoWMI6",
    "sessionTitle": "Equity Through Efficacy: How Collective Beliefs Transform Student Outcomes",
    "sessionDescription": "Discover how Collective Teacher Efficacy (CTE) can serve as a powerful lever for equity in today’s schools. This session shares key findings from a district-level study, highlighting how leadership, trust, and collaboration shape collective beliefs and student outcomes. Participants will explore practical strategies to strengthen CTE, break down systemic barriers, and create more equitable, inclusive learning environments where all students can thrive.",
    "extendedDescription": "In today’s schools, we have seen more and more isolated \"silos\" of teachers and grade levels in each school. This continues to remind us that Collective Efficacy must be built into how educators think, collaborate, and take responsibility for student success. Collective Teacher Efficacy is one of the most powerful drivers of student achievement, yet many schools struggle to intentionally develop it. This session centers on a simple but critical idea: when educators truly believe in their collective ability to impact all students, their actions—and outcomes—change.\n\nDrawing from a district-level mixed-methods study, this session explores how leadership, trust, and collaboration directly influence the development of CTE. Grounded in Bandura’s Social Cognitive Theory, this research highlights a key tension in schools today: while we ask teachers to produce equitable outcomes, we often fail to create the conditions that allow collective belief and shared responsibility to thrive .\n\nThis work is deeply connected to justice-centered education. Equity is about ensuring every student experiences high expectations, strong instruction, and a team of educators who refuse to let them fail. It is so much more than mere access. CTE shifts the focus from individual classrooms to collective ownership. When schools operate from a place of “these are our students,” rather than “my students vs. your students,” systems begin to change. Barriers are challenged. Instruction improves. Outcomes follow.\n\nParticipants will examine key findings around leadership practices that strengthen or weaken collective efficacy, reflect on the current state of trust and collaboration within their own systems, and identify common barriers such as time, fragmentation, and inconsistent expectations. The session will also provide practical, actionable strategies, including strengthening PLC structures, building trust through intentional leadership moves, and using data as a tool for collective problem-solving rather than compliance.\n\nThis session is designed for educators and leaders who are ready to move beyond surface-level collaboration and into meaningful, equity-driven work. Justice-centered education is not about what one teacher can do. but more about what we are willing to believe and accomplish together.",
    "takeaways": [
      "> Understand how Collective Teacher Efficacy (CTE) directly impacts equity and student outcomes",
      "> Identify leadership practices that strengthen trust, collaboration, and shared responsibility",
      "> Recognize common barriers that prevent collective efficacy from developing in schools",
      "> Apply practical strategies to strengthen PLCs and build collective ownership for all students",
      "> Use data as a tool for collective problem-solving rather than compliance"
    ],
