    "id": "speaker-10",
    "name": "Dr. Amy Shelton",
    "role": "Research Fellow & Adjunct Faculty",
    "organization": "Saint Louis University School of Education",
    "bio": "Amy Shelton is a Research Fellow and Adjunct Professor of Education Policy at Saint Louis University, where she previously earned her Ph.D. in Education Policy and Equity. She formerly taught 5th grade in Tulsa, OK through Teach for America, helped coordinate a citywide early literacy intervention summer program, and served as an elected member of the Tulsa Public Schools Board of Education. Her research focuses on the geography of educational opportunity and the relationship between school choice and racial segregation, with a particular focus on greater St. Louis.",
    "presentationExperience": "I have taught three undergraduate courses at SLU and have given multiple guest lectures on topics such as the relationship between housing and school segregation, charter schools, and district open enrollment policies.",
    "image": "https://drive.google.com/u/2/open?usp=forms_web&id=1p3mGSGTWsAxmBUW6XEbefPCgmUKf0s_v",
    "sessionTitle": "Why is St. Louis So Segregated? How Past Housing Discrimination Shaped Districts",
    "sessionDescription": "There are 23 geographic school districts in St. Louis City and County, and district boundary lines can determine which students have access to educational opportunity in our region. Per pupil spending ranges from $11,585/year in Bayless to $23,500/year in Clayton, while percent White ranges from 0.5% to 82.4%. How did this come to be? This presentation examines the history of housing discrimination in St. Louis and how it directly impacts students in schools today.",
    "extendedDescription": "This presentation is based upon an undergraduate course I developed and teach called \"Unveiling the Color Line: Investigating the Formation and Segregation of St. Louis School Districts.” The presentation will start with an investigation of current disparities in table groups. I will share the excellent video Still Separate, Still Unequal (Forward Through Ferguson) and help participants to understand the relationship between school funding, property taxes, and housing discrimination. I will share a brief lecture on the history of racial housing discrimination, including racial zoning, real estate practices, restrictive covenants, redlining, the federal support of White-only suburbs (and the resulting White flight), and how municipal zoning in the county was used to segregate by income and race. Participants will examine interactive maps from the Mapping Decline (Web Project) and St. Louis Public Radio. I will also share a clip from Richard Rothstein’s excellent video Segregated By Design. We will talk briefly about school desegregation and how the current boundary lines were drawn. We will finish our time together discussing opportunities students have had to “cross the color line” through VICC and the Student Transfer Law and consider other policy solutions that have been proposed.",
    "takeaways": [
      "Describe how past racial housing discrimination shaped school district segregation.",
      "Describe the limits of past attempts to address district segregation in our region.",
      "Explain pros/cons of possible policy solutions."
    ],
