    "id": "speaker-20",
    "name": "Antonio Pacifico",
    "role": "Founder",
    "organization": "Mindscape Education Consulting, LLC",
    "bio": "Mindscape is led by Antonio Pacifico, whose education career spans teaching, two successful school turnarounds as a principal, and founding support across New Orleans, Denver, and Saint Louis. Most recently, he successfully launched three new schools in Saint Louis, adding over 600 high-quality seats. He actively shapes the national conversation around high-quality incubation for new school founders.",
    "presentationExperience": "I have led professional development for nearly 14 years across all levels, from teachers and teacher leaders to principals, senior leaders, and executive directors. My experience spans diverse development modalities and audiences, equipping leaders at every tier to drive school improvement. This breadth positions me to design and deliver tailored development strategies for complex, multi-level organizations.",
    "image": "https://drive.google.com/u/2/open?usp=forms_web&id=1PbbgZ2y-OBndwBaQmQeSfeanFqdQe4P8",
    "sessionTitle": "Math for All: Access, Rigor, and Discourse",
    "sessionDescription": "Math achievement gaps don't close through harder problems alone. They close through better teaching. This session equips educators with a coherent framework for math instruction: the three shifts, major work of the grade, and the Concrete Pictorial Abstract progression. Participants then go deeper into how to leverage student models and structured discourse to move more students into rigorous mathematical thinking every lesson, every day.",
    "extendedDescription": "The state of mathematics achievement in the United States is a call to action. Too many students, disproportionately those furthest from opportunity, exit elementary school without the mathematical foundation required for the algebra pathway that opens doors to advanced coursework and long-term economic mobility. This session begins there: with the stakes, and with the conviction that math is for all.\n\nThis session establishes a shared instructional framework grounded in the three major shifts of rigorous math instruction (focus, coherence, and rigor) and traces how they interact across grade levels. Participants explore the major, supporting, and additional work of their grade through Achieve the Core's content maps, developing a coherent picture of where student learning is headed and how each year's work connects to what came before and what comes next. The session makes explicit the connection from kindergarten through fifth grade, helping educators see themselves not as isolated grade-level teachers but as members of one mathematical community building toward Algebra I and beyond.\n\nParticipants will be introduced to the Concrete Pictorial Abstract (CPA) progression as the core vehicle for access and rigor. Through direct application, solving problems in all three modes, participants experience firsthand how CPA widens the entry point for every student without sacrificing mathematical sophistication. Coaches and leaders gain a shared observational lens for what CPA looks like in practice and how to support teachers in implementing it consistently. \n\nThis session embodies Justice-Centered Education for a Changing World at its core. Access to rigorous mathematics is not a luxury. It is a right. When educators build systems for every student to model, explain, and discuss mathematical ideas, they disrupt the tracking and passive learning patterns that have historically excluded students of color and students experiencing poverty from advanced mathematical trajectories. For coaches and leaders, this session provides both the framework and the language to make high-quality math instruction a schoolwide expectation, not a classroom-by-classroom lottery.",
    "takeaways": [
      "Apply the three instructional shifts (focus, coherence, and rigor) to understand and communicate grade-level priorities and vertical connections in math",
      "Use the Concrete Pictorial Abstract (CPA) progression to design and recognize lessons That provide access for all learners while maintaining high cognitive demand",
      "Pre-Identify and leverage student models as instructional tools That generate structured, high-quality mathematical discourse",
      "Plan and facilitate turn and talk sequences That move beyond surface discussion toward deep mathematical reasoning across varied student access levels",
      "Articulate a shared theory of math instruction That positions every student, regardless of background or prior performance, as a capable mathematical thinker"
    ],
