    "sessionTitle": "Building Life Skills Through Journaling: Creative Reflection as a Tool for Education",
    "sessionDescription": "This interactive workshop introduces educators to the power of journaling as a tool for social-emotional learning, confidence-building, creativity, and life skills development in the classroom.\n\nRather than simply discussing journaling strategies, educators will actively participate in several guided activities pulled directly from the Journaling for Life Skills student curriculum. Through reflection, music, creative writing, and discussion, participants will experience firsthand how journaling can support emotional regulation, self-expression, communication, and student engagement.\n\nThis workshop also serves as an introduction to the full 12-Week Journaling for Life Skills Program available for schools, after-school programs, and youth organizations serving students in grades 5–12.",
    "extendedDescription": "“Journaling for Life Skills: Creative Reflection as a Tool for Education” is an interactive workshop designed to help educators integrate journaling, creative expression, and social-emotional learning into their classrooms in ways that support inclusion and student well-being. \nThis session is grounded in the belief that justice-centered education must create space for students to process their emotions, explore their identities, and build confidence in their own perspectives and lived experiences. In a rapidly changing world, students need more than academic instruction alone — they need tools for emotional regulation, self-expression, communication, and reflection when they leave the classroom. Journaling is a skill that supports mental and emotional wellness for students and educators alike. Journaling offers an accessible and low-pressure way to support building crucial skills while helping educators cultivate more human-centered classroom environments.\nRather than presenting journaling as simply a writing exercise, this workshop introduces it as a life skills practice that can be adapted across grade levels and subject areas. Participants will actively engage in several guided activities pulled directly from my 12-week “Journaling for Life Skills” youth program for students in grades 5–12.\nThe session will begin with a brief grounding and reflective writing exercise that models how educators can use low-stakes journaling to create emotionally safe learning spaces and support students entering their classwork with a clear mind. \nParticipants will then experience “The Goal Sun” confidence-building activity, where they identify a personal or professional goal and write affirmations around why they are capable of achieving it. This activity demonstrates how journaling can help students strengthen self-esteem, develop growth mindsets, and recognize their own strengths — particularly for students whose voices and identities are often marginalized in traditional educational settings.\nParticipants will also engage in a rhythm and musical expression activity in which they rewrite the chorus of a familiar song to reflect their current emotions or experiences. This activity highlights the importance of culturally responsive and creative approaches to learning while encouraging students to connect literacy, emotional awareness, and self-expression. Throughout the workshop, educators will discuss how journaling can support students navigating stress, identity development, overwhelm, and interpersonal challenges.\nThe workshop structure includes guided participation, individual reflection, small group discussion, and practical implementation strategies educators can bring back to their classrooms immediately. Participants will leave with concrete journaling prompts, activity ideas, and facilitation approaches that center emotional wellness, creativity, and student agency.\nThis session directly connects to the theme “Justice-Centered Education for a Changing World” by encouraging educators to rethink what student support can look like in today’s classrooms. Justice-centered education requires creating environments where students feel seen, heard, emotionally safe, and empowered to express themselves authentically. By incorporating reflective writing and creative journaling practices into the classroom, educators can build more inclusive learning environments that honor students’ humanity while strengthening the life skills they need to navigate an increasingly complex world.",
