    "sessionTitle": "Justice in Practice: How Schools and Leaders Navigate Discipline Challenges",
    "sessionDescription": "This interactive workshop engages participants in examining justice‑centered approaches to school discipline. Drawing on statewide insights from Missouri, attendees will engage in reflective dialogue and collaborative design activities to explore disproportionality, gaps in current interventions, and the varied resource needs across districts. Participants will identify barriers, promising practices, and co‑develop strategies for creating equitable, inclusive, and safe learning environments for all students.",
    "extendedDescription": "This 90‑minute interactive workshop will invite participants to focus on school climate and culture by transformative vision of school discipline systems in a rapidly changing world. Facilitated by Dr. Chhabra and Dr. Shahid, the session will blend brief research insights with active reflection, small‑group dialogue, and collaborative design activities.\n\nWhile disproportionality in disciplinary consequences is well‑documented, far less is known about the current state of systems-level interventions and resources needed to address it. Grounded in findings from a statewide evaluation of disciplinary practices in Missouri, the workshop will engage participants to explore this structural gap, considering how school and district leaders perceive disciplinary challenges, what preventive or responsive approaches are currently being used, and where implementation barriers continue to limit progress. \n\nThe facilitators will prompt participants to identify the systemic factors that shape disciplinary outcomes—translation of policies into practice, resource allocation, community context, sustainability of existing interventions, and availability of culturally responsive supports in schools. Participants will consider how rural, suburban, and urban districts experience different constraints and opportunities, and how these differences influence the feasibility and sustainability of justice‑centered interventions.\n\nBy the end of the workshop, attendees will leave with a clearer understanding of the current disciplinary landscape, a deeper awareness of the gaps in intervention practice, and a set of co‑created ideas for advancing justice‑centered discipline in their districts and schools.",
    "takeaways": [
      "1.Analyze disciplinary inequities through a justice‑centered lens using statewide insights and reflective dialogue.",
      "2.Identify gaps in current interventions and understand barriers that limit equitable implementation.",
      "3.Assess resource needs across contexts, including differences among rural, suburban, and urban districts.",
      "4.Co‑design actionable strategies to strengthen preventive, inclusive, and culturally responsive discipline practices specific to their context."
    ],
